Watch the way the 49ers are playing, and it’s pretty easy to see why.

The Eagles have played solid ball, and they play “on position” to try and get the jump on the interception, but because they do that, they give up more yards. Their run defense is the weakest part of the defense. Something the 49ers excel at.

49ers don’t have to do that on defense. They can rush four and completely control a bad offensive line. And they can do that all game long. They have such a deep defensive line that they attack your weakest point over and over and over and over. And they add wrinkles with blitzes from linebackers and safeties and corners. And your poor offensive line is just demoralized and crushed and exhausted while they’ve been platooning guys in and out all game who are fresh and rested and ready to go.

On offense it’s even worse. Because they have such excellent skill position players that they will out muscle smaller DBs and out run bigger linebackers. And that’s just the passing game.

Then the running attack is complex and it’s designed to expose the defenses ability to mask what they’re doing pre-snap. It’s why they use so much more motion. They even switch up which personnel groupings they’ll use the most depending on the defense they’ll face.

They want the Lombardi. Badly.

10/10. Padres were hurting for left-handed coverage off the bench and Carpenter can slide into DH role perfectly.

>event A occurs
>non contemporaneous event b which happened in the past must be brought up. Aims to muddle things confuse and spin event A as something more desirable

>Event A occurs
>Pointing out that event A didn't elicit the same responses by some interlocutors as similar event B had done in the past

2/2

Soccer:
- the combination of field size, number of players, speed of ball means that "playmaking" and therefore creating shots and therefore scoring, is extremely difficult and results in very low scoring.
- as a consequence of the first point, this means that the average scoring deviation will be extremely low, which means you will have a very high incidence of ties, shutouts, and games needing to be decided by penalty kicks.
- also related to the first point, this also means that player desperation for goals results in unideal behavior such as faking injuries to try to attain penalty kicks which leads into the slurp that...
- these penalty kicks are desirable because they are extremely punitive and easy to score.
- all of the above leads into situations like the "best game ever" world cup final on sunday which is essentially just a contest of who can get the most penalty kicks, so that they game can be a tie, and decided by penalty kicks.

Tennis:

- not a lot of strategy or creativity involved
- obviously being an individual sport there is no teamwork involved and all the enjoyment that can come from that aspect of sport
- the serve has become too overpowered and needs to be modified. the player serving wins far too high a percentage of games. although that does make break points all the more exciting.

So yeah, they all slurp in some way and it's really all about culture and friends and what you grew up with. They're all great in their own way and they all suck in their own way.

People will tell you it's analytics or game length, but the issue is really money.

MLB is the only one of the big 4 American leagues without a salary cap. If you look at the list of the highest player contracts in the world, more than half are baseball players. So you have teams that have both deep pockets and a high drive to win at any cost that will pay through the nose for the best veterans, then you have teams of more modest means that do what they can, but then you have ones held captive by greedy owners that just pocket whatever shared revenue checks that they're given for the purpose of spending on players. As a result, about a sixth of the teams have fanbases withering on the vine because they don't even have the slightest intention of being competitive now or in the future. Any star player they get their hands on is inevitably traded for peanuts so you can't even get excited for the good times as you know they won't last. Money also drives retarded TV contracts with blackouts, rising ticket costs, and insane payment for concessions.

So you can be priced out of games that you might not be able to see on TV depending on where you live, to see a team that's been in the toilet for over a decade because the owner yet again gave away your best players in a fire sale as your division rival just inked a decade-long $300 million contract. Oh, and the owner is crying poor and that not enough people show up to see that awful team to justify spending more.

Regarding games in general, I think these three basic qualities are what make a good games and inherently enjoyable:
1. It must be easy to learn in regards to offense, defense, scoring (one single way of doing so) and timing. The basic rules regarding these 4 aspects should be summed up in no more than 20 rules.
2. A single game session shouldn't last longer than 2 hours.
3. It must be fluid and prevent interruptions to the core mechanic.
Of all the team ball games, or maybe football codes in particular, I think football (soccer) and rugby league are the best ones in this regard. Add to this a strict enough offside rules in both games that enforce constant teamwork without affecting the scoring possibilities too much, and you get two awesome yet simple games that showcase a great amount of skill, physicality, tactics and coordination. Rugby league I think could and should still be made simpler and do away with the stuff it inherited from union and finally be its own thing, as well as get rid of a few other things, so that it can be the ultimate codification of the "run with the ball / kick it" formula.
The rest of the football codes have either convulted rules (yawnion), too many interruptions and a lack of dynamism (Gridiron, especially American handegg), or it's way too easy to score (Gaelic football and especially Aussie rules). I don't care for indoor team ball games especially because of the "too easy to score" part.
